\begin{align*}
f(-x) &= (-x)^{2}+(a-2)(-x)+1+\cos (-x) \\
&= x^{2}-(a-2)x+1+\cos x.
\end{align*}

Setting $f(-x)$ equal to $f(x)$, we have:
\begin{align*}
x^{2}+(a-2)x+1+\cos x &= x^{2}-(a-2)x+1+\cos x.
\end{align*}

Simplifying the equation, we find that the terms involving $x$ and $\cos x$ cancel out, leaving us with:
\begin{align*}
(a-2)x &= -(a-2)x.
\end{align*}

